The Benue State Government yesterday imposed a 24-hour curfew on Katsina-Ala. This was two days after the killings of 11 people by local militias at Ngibo and Tse-Aye villages in Ikyurav-Tiev 1 in Katsina-Ala Local Government Area. Five people were also said to have been kidnapped earlier in the place on Saturday. Residents were said to have deserted their homes. The acting governor of the state, Benson Abounu, who announced the curfew, said it took effect from yesterday as part of efforts to restore peace and ensure the security of lives and property in the area. He said the curfew would be reviewed as the situation demanded, urging, the people of Katsina-Ala to cooperate with security operatives by obeying the order. He warned that anyone found fomenting trouble in the area or in other parts of the state would be apprehended and punished according to the law. He said more security personnel had been deployed to Katsina-Ala. Earlier, the Force Commander of the Operation Whirl Stroke, Maj.-Gen. Adeyemi Yekini, had said that the crisis which led to the Saturdayâ€™s killings was between the Shitile and Ikyurav people of the area, adding that his troops were already in the area to maintain peace, law and order. JUST IN: Benue govt imposes 24-hour curfew in Kastina-Ala town Intrigues, anxiety as assasins rampage in Benue Intrigues, anxiety as assasins rampage in Benue